<article class="article">
  <div class="article-label">AI — April 2026</div>
  <h1>The Cheat Code That Isn't</h1>
  <div class="article-meta">matterunknown &nbsp;·&nbsp; April 2026 &nbsp;·&nbsp; 7 min read</div>

  <p>The most sophisticated AI sales system on LinkedIn right now is the one being used to sell you an AI sales system.</p>

  <p>You've seen it. A post appears in your feed. It promises to show you the AI workflow that replaced an entire sales team, or the prompt that books 50 meetings a month, or the automation that does in two hours what used to take two weeks. At the bottom, an instruction: <em>Comment "SELL" to get access.</em> Several hundred people comment. The algorithm rewards the engagement. The post reaches thousands more. The person who wrote it captures the leads, sells them a course, and posts again tomorrow.</p>

  <p>This is not AI-powered selling. This is manufactured engagement with AI as the subject line. The AI is not doing the work. The audience is doing the work. They are the product being manufactured, and they are participating willingly because the promise — that there is a shortcut, a system, a secret — is extremely appealing.</p>

  <p>It always has been.</p>

  <h2>The shortcut instinct</h2>

  <p>There is nothing new about the desire to find a faster path. Sales has always attracted people who are looking for leverage, for systems, for the move that changes the game. What changes with each new technology cycle is the specific form the promise takes. In the early social media era it was about follower counts and viral content. Before that it was about SEO hacks and email list growth. The mechanism shifts. The promise is always the same: someone has figured out the thing that makes effort optional, and you can buy access to it.</p>

  <p>AI is the perfect vehicle for this promise right now because it is genuinely, measurably powerful — and because most people don't yet have a calibrated sense of what it can and cannot do. That uncertainty is exploitable. When you don't know where the ceiling is, you're more susceptible to people who claim there isn't one.</p>

  <p>So the gurus position themselves between your confusion and the technology, charge for the crossing, and produce content that perpetuates your dependence on them as the interpreter. It is a good business. It is not a useful service.</p>

  <h2>What AI actually does in sales</h2>

  <p>AI is a force multiplier. This is the correct frame, and it matters that it is accurate. A force multiplier does not change what you are multiplying — it amplifies it. Multiply a weak signal by a large number and you get a large weak signal. Multiply a strong one and you get something genuinely powerful.</p>

  <p>In practice, this means AI is extraordinary at specific, bounded tasks that used to consume large amounts of a salesperson's time. Research — synthesizing everything knowable about a prospect, their company, their recent moves, their competitive position — is something AI does faster and more thoroughly than any human. First drafts of outreach, proposals, and follow-ups. Preparing for objections by modeling the conversation before it happens. Summarizing call transcripts and surfacing the things worth acting on. Scoring leads against criteria that took years of experience to develop.</p>

  <p>All of this is real. None of it is a cheat code. It is a better toolkit applied to the same underlying problem, which has not changed: you need to earn the trust of a specific person who has a specific problem, convince them you can solve it better than the alternatives, and be right about that when it counts.</p>

  <blockquote>The toolkit got better. The game did not get easier. If anything, it got harder, because your competition has the same toolkit.</blockquote>

  <h2>What AI cannot do</h2>

  <p>AI cannot build a relationship. This is not a sentimental observation — it is a functional one. A relationship is built through a series of interactions where one party demonstrates, repeatedly and over time, that they understand the other party's situation well enough to be trusted when it matters. That demonstration requires a person. It requires presence, judgment, and the kind of accumulated context that a model reset between sessions cannot hold.</p>

  <p>AI cannot fix a weak product. If what you're selling doesn't actually solve the problem it claims to solve, better outreach will get you to that conversation faster and more efficiently — and then you will lose it, faster and more efficiently. Volume is not a substitute for substance. Automation of a broken process is a faster broken process.</p>

  <p>AI cannot substitute for domain credibility. When a buyer is deciding whether to trust you with a significant decision, they are running an implicit evaluation of whether you know what you're talking about. That evaluation is based on the quality of your thinking, not the fluency of your prose. A well-written email generated by a model and sent without genuine understanding of the problem is often detectable — not because it reads badly, but because it reads generically. It lacks the specific, grounded insight that comes from actually knowing the domain deeply.</p>

  <p>And AI cannot tell you what to actually do with your pipeline, your customers, or your career. That's what the gurus are selling — judgment wrapped in a framework, packaged as a system. The judgment is theirs. The system is the product. What you get is the packaging.</p>

  <h2>The thing that still wins</h2>

  <p>Relationships and strong product. This is not a nostalgic observation. It is an empirical one. In every market where buyers have real options, the deals that close and the customers that stay are overwhelmingly won by people who know their domain, know their buyer, have something worth buying, and can be trusted to deliver on what they promised.</p>

  <p>AI makes all of these things easier to do well. Research is faster. Preparation is more thorough. Follow-through is more consistent. The best salespeople using AI today are not the ones who found a shortcut — they're the ones who found a way to spend more of their time on the things that actually matter, because AI absorbed the things that didn't.</p>

  <p>That is the force multiplier in action. It requires that you have something worth multiplying. It requires that you understand the problem well enough to know where the leverage is. It requires that you are willing to do the actual work of building trust with actual people over actual time.</p>

  <p>None of that fits in a LinkedIn post. It doesn't generate hundreds of comments. It doesn't produce a lead magnet or a course or a community for $97 a month. It is slow and hard and specific and mostly invisible until it isn't.</p>

  <p>That is why the people selling the cheat code will keep selling it. There is no shortage of demand for shortcuts that don't exist. And there is no better time to sell them than when a genuinely powerful technology has just arrived and most people don't yet know what it can and cannot do.</p>

  <p><em>Know what it can do. Do the rest yourself.</em></p>

